-- China shares finish flat, profit-taking knocks ChiNext from record 
-- By Clement Tan
-- Thu Jan 16, 2014 02:08AM EST
-- None



HONG KONG, Jan 16 (Reuters) - China share indexes stayed broadly flat on Thursday, with strength in non-banking financials balanced by weak banking counters, while profit-taking knocked an index of small cap stocks off a record high.

The CSI300 <.CSI300> of the biggest Shanghai and Shenzhen A-share listings ended up 0.1 percent at 2,211.8 points. The Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> finished flat as volumes stayed lackluster. [ID:nL3N0KQ12S] The ChiNext Composite Index <.CHINEXTC> of mainly startups in technology and other nascent industries listed in Shenzhen sank 1.1 percent after closing on Wednesday at a record high.On Friday, Neway Valve (Suzhou) Co Ltd <603699.SS> will become the first new listing in the mainland since 2012. Authorities this month resumed approvals of initial public offerings following a halt of more than a year. [ID:nL3N0KQ08W]